{"action": "input", "code": "def color_output(output: np.ndarray, colors: List[int]) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes in a numpy array representing a grid of integers and a list of unique colors sorted from the outside to inside of the input grid.\n    It colors the output according to the colors given, notice that it colors the output from outside to inside and every time it colors, only changes one circle.\n    It returns the colored numpy array.\n    \"\"\"\n    n = len(output)\n    mid = n // 2\n    output[mid][mid] = colors[0]\n    for i in range(1, len(colors)):\n        for j in range(mid - i, mid + i + 1):\n            if output[mid - i][j] == 0:\n                output[mid - i][j] = colors[i]\n            if output[mid + i][j] == 0:\n                output[mid + i][j] = colors[i]\n            if output[j][mid - i] == 0:\n                output[j][mid - i] = colors[i]\n            if output[j][mid + i] == 0:\n                output[j][mid + i] = colors[i]\n    return output\ndef main(input_grid):\n    exist_colors = find_and_sort_colors(input_grid)\n    number_colors = len(exist_colors)\n    output = np.zeros((2 * number_colors - 1, 2 * number_colors - 1), dtype=np.int32)\n    output = color_output(output, exist_colors)\n    return output\ndef find_and_sort_colors(input_grid: List[List[int]]) -> List[int]:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes in a 2D list of integers representing a grid of colors.\n    It returns a list of unique colors sorted from the outside to inside of the input grid.\n    \"\"\"\n    exist_colors = set()\n    for i in range(len(input_grid)):\n        for j in range(len(input_grid[0])):\n            exist_colors.add(input_grid[i][j])\n    return sorted(list(exist_colors))", "user_code": "def main(input_grid):\n\texist_colors = `find all the color in the input grid, sort the colors from the outside to inside of the input grid`(input_grid)\n\tnumber_colors = len(exist_colors)\n\toutput = np.zeros((2*number_colors-1, 2*number_colors-1), dtype=np.int32)\n\toutput = `color the output according to the colors given, notice that you should color the output from outside to inside and every time you color, only change one circle`(output, exist_colors)\n\treturn output\n", "gpt_code": "def color_output(output: np.ndarray, colors: List[int]) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes in a numpy array representing a grid of integers and a list of unique colors sorted from the outside to inside of the input grid.\n    It colors the output according to the colors given, notice that it colors the output from outside to inside and every time it colors, only changes one circle.\n    It returns the colored numpy array.\n    \"\"\"\n    n = len(output)\n    mid = n // 2\n    output[mid][mid] = colors[0]\n    for i in range(1, len(colors)):\n        for j in range(mid - i, mid + i + 1):\n            if output[mid - i][j] == 0:\n                output[mid - i][j] = colors[i]\n            if output[mid + i][j] == 0:\n                output[mid + i][j] = colors[i]\n            if output[j][mid - i] == 0:\n                output[j][mid - i] = colors[i]\n            if output[j][mid + i] == 0:\n                output[j][mid + i] = colors[i]\n    return output\ndef find_and_sort_colors(input_grid: List[List[int]]) -> List[int]:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes in a 2D list of integers representing a grid of colors.\n    It returns a list of unique colors sorted from the outside to inside of the input grid.\n    \"\"\"\n    exist_colors = set()\n    for i in range(len(input_grid)):\n        for j in range(len(input_grid[0])):\n            exist_colors.add(input_grid[i][j])\n    return sorted(list(exist_colors))", "holes": {"color_output": "color the output according to the colors given, notice that you should color the output from outside to inside and every time you color, only change one circle", "find_and_sort_colors": "find all the color in the input grid, sort the colors from the outside t